// Accessibility isn't just code - it's mindset!

// ❌ Inaccessible - Image without alt text
<img src="chart.png" />

// ✅ Accessible - Descriptive alt text
<img src="chart.png" alt="Bar chart showing sales increased 50% from Q1 to Q2" />

// ❌ Inaccessible - Button that only works with mouse
<div onClick={handleClick}>Submit</div>

// ✅ Accessible - Real button with keyboard support
<button onClick={handleClick}>Submit</button>

// ❌ Inaccessible - Form without labels
<input type="email" placeholder="Email" />

// ✅ Accessible - Associated label
<label htmlFor="email">Email Address</label>
<input type="email" id="email" />

// ❌ Inaccessible - Low contrast text
<p style={{ color: '#ccc' }}>Light gray text</p>

// ✅ Accessible - High contrast (WCAG AA: 4.5:1 ratio)
<p style={{ color: '#333' }}>Dark gray text on white</p>

// Semantic HTML Examples

function AccessibleCard() {
  // ❌ Generic div soup
  return (
    <div className="card">
      <div className="card-title">Product Name</div>
      <div className="card-desc">Description here</div>
      <div className="card-btn" onClick={buy}>Buy Now</div>
    </div>
  );
}

function AccessibleCard() {
  // ✅ Semantic HTML
  return (
    <article className="card">
      <h3>Product Name</h3>
      <p>Description here</p>
      <button onClick={buy}>Buy Now</button>
    </article>
  );
}

// Navigation
function Nav() {
  return (
    <nav aria-label="Main navigation">
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/" aria-current="page">Home</a></li>
        <li><a href="/about">About</a></li>
        <li><a href="/contact">Contact</a></li>
      </ul>
    </nav>
  );
}

// Form with proper labels
function ContactForm() {
  return (
    <form>
      <div>
        <label htmlFor="name">Full Name</label>
        <input
          type="text"
          id="name"
          name="name"
          required
          aria-required="true"
        />
      </div>

      <div>
        <label htmlFor="email">Email Address</label>
        <input
          type="email"
          id="email"
          name="email"
          required
          aria-describedby="email-help"
        />
        <span id="email-help">We'll never share your email.</span>
      </div>

      <button type="submit">Send Message</button>
    </form>
  );
}

lessons.content:
# Essential to know
- Many users can't or don't use a mouse (keyboard, switch devices, screen readers).
- All interactive elements must be keyboard accessible.
- Tab order should follow visual order (logical flow).
- Visible focus indicators are required.
- Common keys: Tab, Shift+Tab, Enter, Space, Escape, Arrow keys.

---

# Keyboard Navigation: No Mouse Required

## Who Uses Keyboard Navigation?

- **Motor disabilities**: Can't use mouse
- **Blind users**: Screen readers rely on keyboard
- **Power users**: Faster than mouse for many tasks
- **Temporary situations**: Broken mouse, holding baby, bright sun

## Keyboard Basics

**Tab**: Move focus forward
**Shift + Tab**: Move focus backward
**Enter**: Activate button or link
**Space**: Toggle buttons, checkboxes
**Escape**: Close modals, menus
**Arrow keys**: Navigate within widgets

## Making Elements Keyboard Accessible

### Native Elements (Just Work!)

```jsx
// These are automatically keyboard accessible:
<button>Click me</button>
<a href="/about">About</a>
<input type="text" />
<select>...</select>
```

### Custom Elements (Need Help)

```jsx
// ❌ Not keyboard accessible
function BadButton() {
  return (
    <div
      onClick={handleClick}
      style={{ padding: '10px', background: 'blue', color: 'white' }}
    >
      Click me
    </div>
  );
}

// ✅ Keyboard accessible
function GoodButton() {
  return (
    <div
      role="button"
      tabIndex={0}
      onClick={handleClick}
      onKeyDown={(e) => {
        if (e.key === 'Enter' || e.key === ' ') {
          e.preventDefault();
          handleClick();
        }
      }}
      style={{ padding: '10px', background: 'blue', color: 'white' }}
    >
      Click me
    </div>
  );
}

// ✅ Even better - use native button!
function BestButton() {
  return (
    <button onClick={handleClick}>
      Click me
    </button>
  );
}
```

## Focus Management

### Tab Order

Tab order should match visual order (left-to-right, top-to-bottom):

```jsx
// ✅ Logical order
<form>
  <input placeholder="First Name" />  // Tab 1
  <input placeholder="Last Name" />   // Tab 2
  <input placeholder="Email" />       // Tab 3
  <button>Submit</button>               // Tab 4
</form>

// ❌ Illogical order (bad CSS or tabIndex)
<form>
  <input placeholder="Email" tabIndex={3} />       // Tab 3
  <input placeholder="First Name" tabIndex={1} />  // Tab 1
  <button tabIndex={4}>Submit</button>              // Tab 4
  <input placeholder="Last Name" tabIndex={2} />   // Tab 2
</form>
```

**Avoid positive tabIndex values!** Use source order instead.

### Skip Links

Allow keyboard users to skip navigation:

```jsx
function App() {
  return (
    <>
      <a href="#main-content" className="skip-link">
        Skip to main content
      </a>
      <nav>...lots of nav links...</nav>
      <main id="main-content">
        <h1>Page Title</h1>
      </main>
    </>
  );
}
```

```css
.skip-link {
  position: absolute;
  top: -40px;
  left: 0;
  background: #000;
  color: #fff;
  padding: 8px;
  z-index: 100;
}

.skip-link:focus {
  top: 0;
}
```

## Focus Indicators

Users must see where focus is!

```css
/* ❌ Never do this! */
*:focus {
  outline: none;
}

/* ✅ Keep default or provide custom */
*:focus {
  outline: 2px solid blue;
  outline-offset: 2px;
}

/* ✅ Or use box-shadow for rounded elements */
button:focus {
  box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px rgba(66, 153, 225, 0.5);
}
```

## Focus Traps in Modals

When modal opens, trap focus inside:

```jsx
function Modal({ isOpen, onClose, children }) {
  const modalRef = useRef();

  useEffect(() => {
    if (isOpen) {
      // Focus first focusable element
      modalRef.current?.querySelector('button, [href], input').focus();

      // Trap focus
      const handleTab = (e) => {
        const focusable = modalRef.current?.querySelectorAll(
          'button, [href], input, select, textarea, [tabindex]:not([tabindex="-1"])'
        );
        const first = focusable[0];
        const last = focusable[focusable.length - 1];

        if (e.key === 'Tab') {
          if (e.shiftKey && document.activeElement === first) {
            e.preventDefault();
            last.focus();
          } else if (!e.shiftKey && document.activeElement === last) {
            e.preventDefault();
            first.focus();
          }
        }
      };

      document.addEventListener('keydown', handleTab);
      return () => document.removeEventListener('keydown', handleTab);
    }
  }, [isOpen]);

  if (!isOpen) return null;

  return (
    <div className="modal-overlay" onClick={onClose}>
      <div ref={modalRef} className="modal-content" onClick={e => e.stopPropagation()}>
        {children}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Testing Keyboard Navigation

1. **Unplug your mouse**
2. **Use only keyboard** for 5 minutes
3. **Check:**
   - Can you reach every interactive element?
   - Is the tab order logical?
   - Can you see focus indicator?
   - Can you activate everything with Enter/Space?
   - Can you escape modals with Escape key?

